[2]
Date: Tuesday, March 02, 2004 12:01 PM
From: John D Grabenstein, COL OTSG[edited]

Parents whose children have troubles at birth grieve terribly. It is
natural for them to look around for an explanation for why their
lives have been disrupted so. Because unvaccinated parents will have
miscarriages or give birth to children with birth defects, we must
expect vaccinated parents to have the same unfortunate experience.
With regard to the US-licensed anthrax vaccine, we know from
published studies that women vaccinated against anthrax conceive and
give birth to healthy children at the same rate as unvaccinated women
(Wiesen et al. JAMA 2002;287:1556-60). Men vaccinated against
anthrax have sperm of comparable quality and quantity as unvaccinated
men (Catherino et al. Fertility & Sterility 2002;78(Suppl 1);O-285).
We await a final report from a collaborative project between the U.S.
Naval Health Research Center (NHRC) and the Centers for Disease
Control & Prevention (CDC) regarding birth defects and anthrax
vaccine that involves chart review. That collaborative project
responds to preliminary data from a computer-based analysis that
raised a tentative signal that there may be an association with an
increased rate of birth defects if anthrax vaccine was given during
pregnancy; the same analysis showed no elevation in risk for
vaccination before pregnancy. This signal is being investigated
thoroughly, to determine which of several explanations for the signal
is most likely.
Both the US- and UK-licensed anthrax vaccines are inactivated
vaccines, composed of the kinds of proteins that men and women
encounter during everyday life. Because the anthrax vaccine is a
sterile, cell-free (filtered) bacterial vaccine, it is non-infectious
and is not expected to cause any harm to the fetus.
--
Col John Grabenstein RPh PhD
Deputy Director for Military Vaccines
Office of the US Army Surgeon General
Falls Church, VA USA
<grabenstein@otsg.amedd.army.mil>
